
[1]gust

   GUST, n. [L. gustus, gusto; Gr. a contracted word, for it has taste.]

   1. Taste; tasting, or the sense of tasting. More generally, the
   pleasure of tasting; relish.

   2. Sensual enjoyment.

   Where love is duty on the female side,

   On theirs, mere sensual gust, and sought with surly
   pride.

   3. Pleasure; amusement; gratification.

   Destroy all creatures for thy sport or gust.

   4. Turn of fancy; intellectual taste.

   A choice of it may be made according to the gust and manner of the
   ancients. [Taste is now generally used.]

            GUST, v.t. To taste; to have a relish. [Little used.]

                                  GUST, n.

   1. A sudden squall; a violent blast of wind; a sudden rushing or
   driving of the wind, of short duration.

   2. A sudden, violent burst of passion.
